1

00:00:00,000  -->  00:00:01,300
In the previous videos,

2

00:00:01,300  -->  00:00:07,200
we've discussed a simple way to represent each token for our machine learning model.

3

00:00:07,200  -->  00:00:13,380
We were converting each token ID into a vector where all values would be zero,

4

00:00:13,380  -->  00:00:16,380
except for a position equal to vector ID,

5

00:00:16,380  -->  00:00:18,300
which would be set to one.

6

00:00:18,300  -->  00:00:22,825
There is, however, a different way of representing tokens.

7

00:00:22,825  -->  00:00:29,190
Instead, each word can be represented as a smaller multidimensional vector,

8

00:00:29,190  -->  00:00:31,150
where every value would represent

9

00:00:31,150  -->  00:00:35,210
a certain characteristic of a word relevant to our model.

10

00:00:35,210  -->  00:00:37,570
What are the meaning of these values?

11

00:00:37,570  -->  00:00:39,730
Well, we don't set them upfront.

12

00:00:39,730  -->  00:00:42,750
We only decide on what size of vectors we want to

13

00:00:42,750  -->  00:00:46,750
use and then train a model to create these vectors.

14

00:00:46,750  -->  00:00:50,290
These vectors are also called embedding vectors.

15

00:00:50,290  -->  00:00:55,290
The actual meaning of each particular number is not necessarily interpretable.

16

00:00:55,290  -->  00:01:00,490
However, these vectors have some interesting properties we will discuss later.

17

00:01:00,490  -->  00:01:05,190
Embedding vectors usually contain hundreds or even thousands of dimensions.

18

00:01:05,190  -->  00:01:11,050
Unfortunately, we humans are not good at visualizing thousand dimensions vectors.

19

00:01:11,050  -->  00:01:15,410
Instead, we will display two dimensional vectors in this video,

20

00:01:15,410  -->  00:01:18,030
but the properties that we will discuss will be

21

00:01:18,030  -->  00:01:21,220
relevant in real-world embedding vectors as well.

22

00:01:21,220  -->  00:01:25,270
One interesting property of embedding vectors is that words

23

00:01:25,270  -->  00:01:29,550
with similar meanings will be represented by similar vectors.

24

00:01:29,550  -->  00:01:33,990
For example, if we have vectors for words laptop and computer,

25

00:01:33,990  -->  00:01:37,790
they will have similar values and will be close to

26

00:01:37,790  -->  00:01:42,680
all other vectors representing words related to computers and tech.

27

00:01:42,680  -->  00:01:47,490
On the other hand, if we have another group of words like orange and banana,

28

00:01:47,490  -->  00:01:49,330
they will be close to each other,

29

00:01:49,330  -->  00:01:53,330
but they will be far away from technology related vectors.

30

00:01:53,330  -->  00:01:56,710
Given two vectors in a multidimensional space,

31

00:01:56,710  -->  00:01:59,515
we can compute how similar they are.

32

00:01:59,515  -->  00:02:02,630
To do this, we can use an operation called

33

00:02:02,630  -->  00:02:06,330
dot product that works for vectors of any size.

34

00:02:06,330  -->  00:02:11,650
But we will see how it works using an example of three dimensional vectors.

35

00:02:11,650  -->  00:02:15,090
Dot product is represented using a dot symbol,

36

00:02:15,090  -->  00:02:17,600
and it is computed in the following way.

37

00:02:17,600  -->  00:02:19,120
To calculate dot product,

38

00:02:19,120  -->  00:02:24,580
we take the first pair of values from both vectors and multiply them together.

39

00:02:24,580  -->  00:02:29,320
We then take the second pair and multiply them together as well.

40

00:02:29,320  -->  00:02:35,900
Then the next pair, and then we add the result of these three pairwise multiplications.

41

00:02:35,900  -->  00:02:38,405
This is a result of the dot product.

42

00:02:38,405  -->  00:02:41,950
Mathematically, dot product is the final exist.

43

00:02:41,950  -->  00:02:45,460
We multiply a pair of values for each position,

44

00:02:45,460  -->  00:02:49,380
and then we sum up these multiplication results together.

45

00:02:49,380  -->  00:02:53,260
Now, how do we interpret the result of a dot product?

46

00:02:53,260  -->  00:02:55,280
If the result is positive,

47

00:02:55,280  -->  00:02:59,820
it means that vectors are similar like on the image on the right,

48

00:02:59,820  -->  00:03:03,560
which in turn means that the words have similar meaning.

49

00:03:03,560  -->  00:03:05,780
The greater the value of a dot product,

50

00:03:05,780  -->  00:03:08,590
the greater the similarity between two words.

51

00:03:08,590  -->  00:03:11,460
If the dot product result is close to zero,

52

00:03:11,460  -->  00:03:14,400
it means that the words are unrelated.

53

00:03:14,400  -->  00:03:16,540
For example, these can be words from

54

00:03:16,540  -->  00:03:20,615
completely different domains like technology and food.

55

00:03:20,615  -->  00:03:23,410
If the dot product is negative,

56

00:03:23,410  -->  00:03:28,850
it means that the words have opposite meanings like words hot and cold.

57

00:03:28,850  -->  00:03:32,990
Another interesting property of embedding vectors is that we can

58

00:03:32,990  -->  00:03:37,850
perform mass operation between them and get interesting results.

59

00:03:37,850  -->  00:03:39,950
A classic example is,

60

00:03:39,950  -->  00:03:46,650
if we take a vector for the word woman and subtract the vector for the word man from it,

61

00:03:46,650  -->  00:03:50,160
and then add the result vector to the word king.

62

00:03:50,160  -->  00:03:56,960
We will get a vector that is very close to the vector that represents the word queen.

63

00:03:56,960  -->  00:03:59,920
If we reorder this expression a bit,

64

00:03:59,920  -->  00:04:04,380
we will have an expression that says that the difference between word queen and

65

00:04:04,380  -->  00:04:09,260
king is similar to the difference between the words woman and man.

66

00:04:09,260  -->  00:04:12,520
Other vectors have similar relationships.

67

00:04:12,520  -->  00:04:16,480
For example, difference between mother and father,

68

00:04:16,800  -->  00:04:21,120
also similar to difference between words women and men.

69

00:04:21,120  -->  00:04:26,120
Another interesting relationship is if we subtract Rome from Paris,

70

00:04:26,120  -->  00:04:29,560
it will be similar to the difference between France and Italy,

71

00:04:29,560  -->  00:04:32,750
and if we subtract Europe from euro,

72

00:04:32,750  -->  00:04:36,715
It will be similar to the difference between dollar and America.

73

00:04:36,715  -->  00:04:39,470
There are two ways to get word embeddings.

74

00:04:39,470  -->  00:04:44,310
One way we can use an independent model that was trained specifically to compute

75

00:04:44,310  -->  00:04:49,930
word embeddings for a particular vocabulary, unrelated to transformers.

76

00:04:49,930  -->  00:04:53,770
You can download these models and use them in your applications.

77

00:04:53,770  -->  00:04:56,710
However, when we're training a transformer model,

78

00:04:56,710  -->  00:05:00,690
it will learn word embeddings as part of its training process,

79

00:05:00,690  -->  00:05:03,910
so we don't need a separate library in this case.

80

00:05:03,910  -->  00:05:07,090
To wrap up our conversation of embedding vectors,

81

00:05:07,090  -->  00:05:11,180
let's briefly talk about how we could use them in a simple model.

82

00:05:11,180  -->  00:05:13,050
Having an input sentence,

83

00:05:13,050  -->  00:05:18,150
we can tokenize it and convert each token into a separate embedding vector.

84

00:05:18,150  -->  00:05:23,830
We can then flatten this vector and pass it into a feed forward neural network.

85

00:05:23,830  -->  00:05:26,970
However, instead of using a feed forward network,

86

00:05:26,970  -->  00:05:29,390
we can also use architectures designed

87

00:05:29,390  -->  00:05:33,430
specifically for processing sequential data like text.

88

00:05:33,430  -->  00:05:37,910
This is something that we will look into in the next videos.
